From: experintellia <280144245+experintellia@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Fri, 10 Jul 2026 20:39:56 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 39/39] web-app: probe a webimap route, not /, in the madmail
 pre-flight
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The CORS pre-flight added in the previous webimap-setup patch probed
GET <base>/, assuming madmail serves CORS headers on the index page too.
It does not: madmail applies Access-Control-Allow-Origin only to /new
and the /webimap/* / /websmtp/* API routes (chatmail-www's router wires
the CORS snapshot into those handlers only), so the probe threw for
every madmail server — including correctly configured ones — and the
dialog showed the 'reachable but CORS-blocked' false negative on each
first submit.

Probe GET <base>/webimap/mailboxes instead. Without auth headers it is
just a 401, side-effect-free, and the response goes through the same
CORS policy (including the webimap-enabled gate) that answers the
core's later requests — so cors-mode fetch resolving really does mean
the server is usable from the browser, and failing still means webimap
is disabled or CORS is not set up.

Co-Authored-By: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 .../WelcomeScreen/UseWebimapServerDialog.tsx  | 30 ++++++++++++-------
 1 file changed, 19 insertions(+), 11 deletions(-)

diff --git a/packages/frontend/src/components/screens/WelcomeScreen/UseWebimapServerDialog.tsx b/packages/frontend/src/components/screens/WelcomeScreen/UseWebimapServerDialog.tsx
index 8dc33fec9..100b98a0a 100644
--- a/packages/frontend/src/components/screens/WelcomeScreen/UseWebimapServerDialog.tsx
+++ b/packages/frontend/src/components/screens/WelcomeScreen/UseWebimapServerDialog.tsx
@@ -62,31 +62,39 @@ function webimapBaseUrl(host: string): string {
  * A cross-origin `fetch` that fails throws the same opaque TypeError whether
  * the cause is CORS or a dead host — the browser hides the difference on
  * purpose. So we probe twice:
- *   - a normal (`cors`) GET to `<base>/` resolves (for any HTTP status) only if
- *     the server sent an Access-Control-Allow-Origin the app's origin is
- *     allowed by;
+ *   - a normal (`cors`) GET to `<base>/webimap/mailboxes` resolves (for any
+ *     HTTP status — without auth headers it's just a 401) only if the server
+ *     sent an Access-Control-Allow-Origin the app's origin is allowed by;
  *   - if that throws, a `no-cors` GET resolves (as an opaque response) as long
  *     as the server is reachable at all, CORS headers or not.
  * cors-ok → 'ok'; cors-throws + no-cors-ok → 'cors'; both throw →
  * 'unreachable'.
  *
+ * The probe must target a webimap route: madmail applies CORS headers only to
+ * `/new` and the `/webimap/*` / `/websmtp/*` API routes, never to the `/`
+ * index page, so probing `/` flags every madmail server — including correctly
+ * configured ones — as CORS-blocked. `GET /webimap/mailboxes` is the
+ * side-effect-free choice (unlike POST /new, which would provision an
+ * account), and it is gated by the same CORS policy that will answer the
+ * core's later requests, including whether webimap is enabled at all.
+ *
  * This is a best-effort heuristic, not a guarantee — the caller only warns on
- * it (the user can proceed anyway). Caveats: it probes `/` (side-effect-free,
- * unlike POST /new which would provision an account), assuming madmail serves
- * CORS headers on `/` too; and a plain GET is a CORS "simple request", so an
- * 'ok' here does not prove the later preflighted requests (the auth-header
- * `GET /webimap/*` calls) will pass. On its own errors it returns 'ok' so a
- * flaky probe never blocks a server that would in fact work.
+ * it (the user can proceed anyway). Caveat: a plain GET is a CORS "simple
+ * request", so an 'ok' here does not prove the later preflighted requests
+ * (the auth-header `GET /webimap/*` calls) will pass — though madmail answers
+ * preflights from the same CORS policy this GET exercises. On its own errors
+ * it returns 'ok' so a flaky probe never blocks a server that would in fact
+ * work.
  */
 async function diagnoseWebimapServer(
   host: string
 ): Promise<'ok' | 'cors' | 'unreachable'> {
-  const base = `${webimapBaseUrl(host)}/`
+  const probeUrl = `${webimapBaseUrl(host)}/webimap/mailboxes`
   const reaches = async (mode: RequestMode): Promise<boolean> => {
     const controller = new AbortController()
     const timer = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), 6000)
     try {
-      await fetch(base, {
+      await fetch(probeUrl, {
         method: 'GET',
         mode,
         cache: 'no-store',
